[3]
Date: 16 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Singapore - Ministry of Health 16 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://app.moh.gov.sg/sar/sar0301.asp?id=1&mid=6180>


SARS Situation Update 16 Apr 2003

As of 16 Apr 2003, 6 additional SARS patients have been discharged,
bringing the total number of patients who have recovered from SARS to 91.
61 SARS patients remain hospitalised.

There are 5 additional SARS cases reported today. They comprise 2 staff
members of National Cancer Centre (NCC), namely a radiographer who had been
admitted to Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH) since 9 Apr 2003 for observation,
and a porter who was admitted to TTSH on 14 Apr 2003. Both patients
developed lung changes on chest X-ray yesterday and hence were diagnosed to
have SARS. The third SARS case is an inpatient at Singapore General
Hospital (SGH) Ward 58 who has been observed in TTSH since 13 Apr 2003, and
who developed lung changes yesterday. The other 2 cases comprise the son of
a SARS patient, and a doctor at National University Hospital (NUH) who
looked after 2 patients prior to their diagnosis of SARS.

Situation Update at NCC
There are 2 NCC staff members who have been diagnosed as probable SARS.

The radiographer developed a fever (37.8 deg C) on Saturday 5 Apr 2003. He
did not see a doctor. He was well with no fever over the next 3 days (6--8
Apr 2003). He worked in the radiology department of NCC on 7 and 8 Apr
2003. Twice-daily temperature monitoring was performed and he was noted to
have no fever. During these 2 days, he performed CT scans and MRI on a
total of 11 patients.

In the early hours of 9 Apr 2003, he developed fever of 38.4 deg C. He went
to Changi General Hospital (CGH) and was transferred to TTSH on the same
day. On admission he was classified as a low-risk suspect for SARS. CGH
observed all the infection control measures when the patient was there.

Another hospital staff (porter), who handles dispatch work, developed a
low-grade fever (37.5 deg C) on the morning of Thu 10 Apr 2003. He was not
assigned any duties and during that time he only came into contact with the
departmental staff. At noon, his temperature went up to 38.6 deg C. He was
seen at the SGH Staff Clinic and was given 2 days MC [medical leave?] and
asked to return for a review on 12 Apr 2003.

He had no fever on 11 Apr 2003. He did not return to the Staff Clinic on 12
Apr 2003 and instead saw his neighbourhood General Practitioner (GP). He
was given 2 more days MC. He continued to have low-grade [fever]. On 14 Apr
2003, he went directly to the Staff Clinic and was referred to TTSH and
admitted on the same day.

Besides these 2 staff members, the other NCC staff are currently well. As a
precaution, NCC has closed its radiology department until 20 Apr 2003.
Urgent radiological x-rays will be done at SGH A&E Dept. Non-urgent
appointments will be deferred. NCC has contacted 10 of the 11 patients who
had X-ray investigations done by the radiographer and they are well.
Although the radiographer did not go into the waiting room of the X-ray
department, as a precaution, NCC has been contacting the 200 patients who
have had other X-rays done during the period 7--9 Apr 2003. Investigations
are still in progress to trace the source of infection.

Situation Update at NUH
The doctor attended to a patient who was being treated for heart failure.
The patient, who was admitted to NUH on 8 Apr 2003, had been a visitor at
SGH Ward 57 in end March. He had multiple medical conditions and did not
have fever at that time. When he was reviewed in the ward, the possibility
of concurrent pneumonia was recognised as his condition had deteriorated.
The patient was unstable and required transfer to the NUH Intensive Care
Unit where he was intubated. The transfer to TTSH took place later on the
same day when the patient's condition stabilised. The patient passed away
on 12 Apr 2003.

The NUH doctor developed fever on 11 Apr 2003 evening and was sent to TTSH
Emergency Department on the same day. She has been diagnosed as a probable
SARS case on 16 Apr 2003.

Home Quarantine for non-SARS patients with chronic conditions discharged
from SGH and TTSH
Contact tracing at SGH has identified the patients and healthcare workers
who may have been exposed to SARS. These contacts have been quarantined or
are being monitored. There are about 800 inpatients at present in SGH who
have not been exposed. However, as a precaution, patients discharged from
SGH from 17 Apr 2003 onwards who have chronic co-morbid conditions will be
issued Home Quarantine Orders (HQO) for 10 days. At end of 10 days, SGH
will recall them for review, following which they will be on phone
surveillance for a further 10 days. The other discharged patients who do
not have any chronic conditions will not be on HQO but phone surveillance
for 21 days. The same arrangement will be implemented for non-SARS patients
with chronic conditions discharged from TTSH.

Summary of SARS cases
There was a SARS patient in intensive care who died late 15 Apr 2003. She
was the mother of a doctor who contracted SARS while looking after a SARS
patient. The other deceased is the mother of a SARS patient. On 13 Apr
2003, we reported 2 SARS deaths linked to the SGH cluster comprising an
inpatient and the brother of an index patient. The preliminary findings of
both patients were that they died of other medical conditions unrelated to
SARS. We are awaiting results of further investigations.

Below is the summary of the SARS cases to date:

Number Discharged: 85 plus 6
Hospitalised: 61 (including 16 in intensive care)
Deaths: 13 + 2 (pending post mortem findings)

Total: 167

Suspected: 91 (including 8 children below 18)
Under home quarantine orders: 582

