[5]
Date: 16 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada [edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/sars/update32.html>


Update 32: Severe acute respiratory syndrome -- 16 Apr 2003 4:30 PM

As of 16 Apr 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 303 probable or
suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in Canada. There
have been 13 deaths in Canada. To date, transmission has been limited to
specific transmission settings such as households, hospitals, and specific
community settings. The information contained in this update is based on
the information available to Health Canada at this time.

The details of the cases to date are as follows:

Ontario is reporting 122 probable and 127 suspect cases. All cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 4 probable and 38 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting 2 suspect cases.
Saskatchewan is reporting 1 suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 5 suspect cases.
Prince Edward Island is reporting 4 suspect cases.

So far, 91 people have been discharged from hospitals in Ontario. These
people were treated as suspect cases or as probable cases.

These numbers are accurate as of 1:00 PM EDST 16 Apr 2003.

[These data do not mention the newswire reports of transmission within a
religious community related to attendance at a funeral of a probable SARS
case. The newswire reports have been varied, with some mentioning that
most of the cases had been previously reported, but according to this
update there is no mention of community-based close contact, which appeared
to be the mode of transmission in this generation of cases. More
information on this observation from official sources would be appreciated.
- Mod.MPP]

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As of today's update there is a cumulative total of 3293 cases of SARS
reported to the WHO, with 58 new cases reported in the preceding 24 hours;
a total of 159 deaths (case fatality rate of 4.8 percent) and 1548 patients
have recovered (47 percent). In the past 24 hours, Hong Kong has reported
36 new cases and 5 deaths; in China there have been 14 new cases
reported. Based on the information provided by Dr. Heymann in today's WHO
press briefing, we expect to see the numbers of cases reported from Beijing
to increase significantly once official reports from the military hospitals
are received. In addition, there has been the suggestion of increased
transmission outside of Beijing and Guangdong. It would be interesting to
see a breakdown of reported cases by province to determine whether new
areas of local transmission have been identified. For example, the lay
press has reported cases in Inner Mongolia, suggesting local transmission,
but this area has not officially been added to the affected areas list --
see ProMED-mail posting SARS - worldwide (45): cases 20030412.0890.

There are now 199 suspected cases from 32 states in the United States. This
represents an increase of 6 cases from the last report on 15 Apr
2003. There has been mention in press releases (CDC press release 14 Apr
2003 (accessible at:
<http://www.cdc.gov/od/oc/media/transcripts/t030414.htm> and in many lay
press reports) that the USA plans to change reporting practices, separating
suspected and probable cases using the WHO definitions. When that occurs,
we expect to see a marked decrease in the numbers of cases of SARS reported
on a daily basis to WHO. - Mod.MPP]
